Of the 17 families of siphonostomatoids infecting vertebrates (
), representatives of 14 are reported from Southern African water ( Fig. 1 ). In 2004 (
) the reported 15 families included the Euryphoridae that now forms part of the Caligidae and the Cecropidae that now is part of the
Pandaridae ( Walter & Boxshall 2024 )
. The newly reported family is Hyponeoidae ( Table 1 ). The families which have not been reported include the Archidactylinidae infecting hagfishes ( Myxiniformes : Myxinidae ) (
), Pseudohatschekiidae collected from deepwater tilefishes (Teleostei: Latilidae ) (
) and Tanypleuridae infecting the arctic eelpout (Teleostei: Zoarcidae ) (
). The combination of the 2004 (
) reports as well as the updates ( Table 1 ) and new reports ( Table 2 ) include 73 different genera and 231 species (excluding reports of unidentified species) from vertebrate hosts. Since the 2004 report (
), 15 additional species are reported in the Caligidae , 11 in the Eudactylinidae , one in Hyponeoidae , eight in Kroyeriidae , 11 in Lernaeopodidae , six in Pandaridae , eight in Pennellidae , 10 in Sphyriidae and one in Trebiidae . The family with the most reported species is Caligidae (69 species) which still is very low considering that Caligidae currently has about 499 accepted species (
) ( Fig. 1 ). This is followed by the Lernaeopodidae (36 species) currently with about 329 accepted species (
) ( Fig. 1 ). From these two examples it is clear that there are still many species to be reported from Southern African waters specifically considering the diversity of possible hosts occurring off South Africa (
).

An update regarding the knowledge about the diversity of siphonostomatoids infecting marine organisms off Southern Africa is required since the last comprehensive report was published 20 years ago (in 2004) (Dippenaar 1994). The previous list only included siphonostomatoids infecting marine fish off Southern Africa. Apart from reports published since 2004 and species with changed taxonomy, unreported siphonostomatoids are also included in the current report. Therefore, the current knowledge regarding the biodiversity of 
Siphonostomatoida
off Southern Africa includes 16 families, 75 genera and 234 species reported from vertebrates and invertebrates. New information about the state of our current knowledge as well as new host and geographic localities of the reported siphonostomatoids are provided. Furthermore, all records are combined in a single report (together with the 2004 report) with the latest references of additional reports since 2004 which will be very helpful to new researchers. Even though taxonomy is a living subject with “refutable scientific hypotheses” (

) and changes in taxonomy can always be expected (especially in large families like 
Lernaeopodidae
), the current report will be a good starting point for anybody interesting in marine symbiotic siphonostomatoids off Southern Africa. Although there is an improvement in the reported biodiversity it is unfortunate that numbers are still very low compared with accepted numbers of species (

), especially considering the diversity of possible hosts (vertebrates and invertebrates) occurring off Southern Africa.
